---
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "What is real estate marketing automation?",
    answer:
      "It is a connected workflow that triggers campaigns, coordinates messages across channels, routes engaged leads into CRM follow-up, and tracks which activities create qualified opportunities.",
  },
  {
    question: "What should a marketing automation workflow include?",
    answer:
      "A practical system includes audience segmentation, campaign entry rules, email or SMS sequencing, CRM handoff logic, nurture paths, and reporting tied to qualified outcomes.",
  },
  {
    question: "When should a real estate team invest in marketing automation?",
    answer:
      "It becomes useful once the team already runs campaigns or publishes content regularly and needs more reliable execution, handoff, and reporting across channels.",
  },
  {
    question: "What metrics matter most for real estate marketing automation?",
    answer:
      "Track response rate, qualified lead rate, consultation bookings, conversion by campaign, and source-to-client performance to see whether the workflow improves real business results.",
  },
];
---

<MainLayout
  title="Real Estate Marketing Automation | Realty Efficiency Hub"
  description="Real estate marketing automation for campaign triggers, nurture sequences, CRM handoff, audience segmentation, and clearer conversion reporting."
  image="/images/posts/real-estate-marketing-automation-cover.svg"
>
  <section class="solution-shell">
    <div class="eyebrow">Solution</div>
    <div class="hero-grid">
      <div>
        <h1>Real Estate Marketing Automation</h1>
        <p class="intro">
          Real estate marketing automation connects campaigns, nurture timing, CRM handoff,
          and reporting so more marketing activity turns into qualified conversations.
          It is most valuable when the team already creates content and campaigns, but execution still feels fragmented.
        </p>

        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a href="/blog/real-estate-marketing-automation" class="primary-link">See the marketing workflow guide</a>
          <a href="/blog/listing-marketing-automation" class="secondary-link">See listing marketing examples</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <figure class="hero-visual">
        <img
          src="/images/posts/real-estate-marketing-automation-diagram.svg"
          alt="Real estate marketing automation workflow diagram"
          loading="eager"
        />
      </figure>
    </div>

    <section class="quick-answer">
      <h2>The Short Version</h2>
      <p>
        A good real estate marketing automation system should segment the audience, trigger the right campaign,
        coordinate follow-up across email, SMS, social, or tasks, and send engaged leads into the CRM with enough context
        for sales follow-up to continue without friction.
      </p>

      <div class="glance-grid">
        <article class="glance-card">
          <h3>Best for</h3>
          <p>Teams running campaigns regularly but struggling to connect execution, nurture, and pipeline outcomes.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="glance-card">
          <h3>Main outcome</h3>
          <p>More reliable campaign execution and better conversion from marketing activity into qualified opportunities.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="glance-card">
          <h3>What to automate first</h3>
          <p>Audience entry rules, campaign sequencing, handoff triggers, and weekly reporting loops.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="summary-box">
      <h2>What this solution should improve</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>campaign execution speed and consistency</li>
        <li>alignment between marketing and CRM follow-up</li>
        <li>multi-channel nurture tied to intent and stage</li>
        <li>clearer visibility into which campaigns create qualified opportunities</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <h2>How the marketing automation should work</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">
            Readers should be able to understand the core operating idea quickly:
            campaigns are not just content pushes, they are structured workflows with triggers, branches, and handoff logic.
          </p>
        </div>
        <img
          class="inline-visual"
          src="/images/posts/real-estate-marketing-automation-cover.svg"
          alt="Real estate marketing automation cover illustration"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>

      <div class="steps-grid">
        <article class="step-card">
          <h3>1. Define campaign entry</h3>
          <p>New inquiries, open house attendees, listing watchers, and dormant leads should not enter the same flow.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="step-card">
          <h3>2. Coordinate channels</h3>
          <p>Email, SMS, social prompts, and CRM tasks should work together on a practical timeline instead of in isolation.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="step-card">
          <h3>3. Trigger live follow-up</h3>
          <p>When the lead engages meaningfully, the workflow should create the right human next step with context attached.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="step-card">
          <h3>4. Review and tune weekly</h3>
          <p>The system should produce enough reporting to improve message timing, segmentation, and conversion quality over time.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Where teams usually get stuck</h2>
      <p>
        Many teams can create campaigns, but they struggle to coordinate what happens after launch.
        Message timing slips, follow-up ownership gets fuzzy, and reporting arrives too late to improve results.
      </p>
      <p>
        Real estate marketing automation works best when it is tied directly to operational workflows,
        not isolated inside a newsletter tool or social scheduler.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Best-fit use cases</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>teams running frequent campaigns with weak operational follow-through</li>
        <li>brokerages or agents managing multiple lead sources</li>
        <li>listing promotion systems that need better nurture and attribution</li>
        <li>teams scaling content output without clear process control</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Why this page is stronger for search intent</h2>
      <p>
        Someone searching for real estate marketing automation usually wants a system view, not just a surface definition.
        They want to know what the workflow includes, what results it should improve, and which parts are worth automating first.
      </p>
      <p>
        This structure gives the short answer near the top, then expands into implementation detail for readers who want more depth.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        {faqs.map((faq) => (
          <article class="faq-item">
            <h3>{faq.question}</h3>
            <p>{faq.answer}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section related">
      <h2>Supporting articles published by March 19, 2026</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="/blog/real-estate-marketing-automation">Real Estate Marketing Automation Workflow</a>
        <a href="/blog/real-estate-marketing-prompts">Real Estate Marketing Prompts</a>
        <a href="/blog/open-house-marketing-prompts">Open House Marketing Prompts</a>
        <a href="/blog/open-house-lead-automation">Open House Lead Automation</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>

  <script is:inline type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    mainEntity: faqs.map((faq) => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      name: faq.question,
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: faq.answer,
      },
    })),
  })} />

  <style>
    .solution-shell {
      max-width: 980px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 24px 0;
    }

    .eyebrow {
      display: inline-block;
      margin-bottom: 14px;
      padding: 6px 12px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: #eef4ff;
      color: #1d4ed8;
      font-size: 13px;
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    }

    .hero-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.3fr) minmax(280px, 0.9fr);
      gap: 24px;
      align-items: center;
      margin-bottom: 24px;
    }

    h1 {
      margin: 0 0 16px 0;
      font-size: 50px;
      line-height: 1.04;
      color: #0f172a;
    }

    .intro {
      margin: 0;
      font-size: 19px;
      line-height: 1.75;
      color: #475569;
      max-width: 820px;
    }

    .hero-actions {
      display: flex;
      gap: 12px;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      margin-top: 24px;
    }

    .primary-link,
    .secondary-link {
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 12px 16px;
      font-weight: 700;
      text-decoration: none;
    }

    .primary-link {
      background: #2563eb;
      color: #ffffff;
    }

    .secondary-link {
      background: #ffffff;
      border: 1px solid #dbe4ee;
      color: #0f172a;
    }

    .hero-visual,
    .summary-box,
    .quick-answer,
    .section {
      margin: 0 0 22px 0;
      padding: 24px;
      background: #ffffff;
      border: 1px solid #dbe4ee;
      border-radius: 20px;
      box-shadow: 0 10px 28px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.05);
    }

    .hero-visual {
      padding: 14px;
      background: linear-gradient(180deg, #f8fbff 0%, #ffffff 100%);
    }

    .hero-visual img,
    .inline-visual {
      width: 100%;
      display: block;
      border-radius: 16px;
    }

    h2 {
      margin: 0 0 12px 0;
      font-size: 30px;
      color: #0f172a;
    }

    h3 {
      margin: 0 0 8px 0;
      font-size: 20px;
      color: #0f172a;
    }

    p,
    li {
      color: #475569;
      font-size: 17px;
      line-height: 1.75;
    }

    ul {
      margin: 0;
      padding-left: 20px;
    }

    .glance-grid,
    .steps-grid {
      display: grid;
      gap: 14px;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
      margin-top: 18px;
    }

    .glance-card,
    .step-card {
      padding: 18px;
      border-radius: 16px;
      background: #f8fbff;
      border: 1px solid #dbe4ee;
    }

    .glance-card p,
    .step-card p,
    .section-intro {
      margin: 0;
    }

    .section-head {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.2fr) minmax(240px, 0.8fr);
      gap: 18px;
      align-items: start;
      margin-bottom: 18px;
    }

    .related-grid {
      display: grid;
      gap: 12px;
    }

    .faq-list {
      display: grid;
      gap: 14px;
    }

    .faq-item {
      padding: 18px;
      border-radius: 16px;
      background: #f8fbff;
      border: 1px solid #dbe4ee;
    }

    .faq-item h3,
    .faq-item p {
      margin: 0;
    }

    .faq-item p {
      margin-top: 8px;
    }

    .related-grid a {
      text-decoration: none;
      color: #1d4ed8;
      font-weight: 700;
    }

    .related-grid a:hover {
      color: #1e40af;
    }

    @media (max-width: 820px) {
      .hero-grid,
      .section-head {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      }

      h1 {
        font-size: 40px;
      }

      .intro {
        font-size: 18px;
      }
    }
  </style>
</MainLayout>
